The reaction with liquid reactants can be written as the sum of the vaporisation steps followed by the combustion of the gases:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\text{CH}_4(l) &\rightarrow \text{CH}_4(g) \qquad \Delta H_{\text{vap}}(\text{CH}_4)=+8.2\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}\\
2\,\text{O}_2(l) &\rightarrow 2\,\text{O}_2(g) \qquad 2\Delta H_{\text{vap}}(\text{O}_2)=2(+6.8)=+13.6\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}\\
\text{CH}_4(g)+2\text{O}_2(g) &\rightarrow \text{CO}_2(g)+2\text{H}_2\text{O}(g) \qquad \Delta H_{\text{comb}}=-890.8\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

Adding these steps gives the overall enthalpy change for  

\[
\text{CH}_4(l)+2\text{O}_2(l)\rightarrow \text{CO}_2(g)+2\text{H}_2\text{O}(g)
\]

\[
\Delta H = \Delta H_{\text{vap}}(\text{CH}_4) + 2\Delta H_{\text{vap}}(\text{O}_2) + \Delta H_{\text{comb}}
          = 8.2\ \text{kJ} + 13.6\ \text{kJ} - 890.8\ \text{kJ}
          = -869\ \text{kJ}
\]

