### 2.  Limiting reagent  

Each mole of \(\mathrm{LiCoO_{2}}\) supplies one mole of Li⁺, which requires **6 mol of C** to form \(\mathrm{LiC_{6}}\).

\[
\text{C needed}=6\,n_{\mathrm{LiCoO_{2}}}=6(0.1022)=0.613\;\text{mol}
\]

Since \(n_{\mathrm{C}}=0.8325\;\text{mol}>0.613\;\text{mol}\), \(\mathrm{LiCoO_{2}}\) is the limiting reagent.  
All \(0.1022\;\text{mol}\) of Li⁺ are transferred to the anode.

