The added lactic acid supplies the extra protons that are taken up by the bicarbonate buffer:

\[
\mathrm{H}^{+}+ \mathrm{HCO_3^-}\;\rightleftharpoons\; \mathrm{H_2CO_3}
\]

The total inorganic carbon concentration \(C_{\text{T}}\) remains constant, so we first determine it at the initial pH 7.40.

\[
\begin{aligned}
[\mathrm{H}^{+}]_i &=10^{-7.40}=3.98\times10^{-8}\ \text{M}\\[2mm]
[\mathrm{H_2CO_3}]_i &=\frac{[\mathrm{H}^{+}]_i[\mathrm{HCO_3^-}]_i}{K_{a1}}
                     =\frac{(3.98\times10^{-8})(0.022)}{4.5\times10^{-7}}
                     =1.95\times10^{-3}\ \text{M}\\[2mm]
[\mathrm{CO_3^{2-}}]_i &=\frac{K_{a2}[\mathrm{HCO_3^-}]_i}{[\mathrm{H}^{+}]_i}
                       =\frac{(4.7\times10^{-11})(0.022)}{3.98\times10^{-8}}
                       =2.60\times10^{-5}\ \text{M}
\end{aligned}
\]

\[
C_{\text{T}}=[\mathrm{HCO_3^-}]_i+[\mathrm{H_2CO_3}]_i+[\mathrm{CO_3^{2-}}]_i
            =0.022+1.95\times10^{-3}+2.60\times10^{-5}
            =2.397\times10^{-2}\ \text{M}
\]

At the final pH 7.00 (\([\mathrm{H}^{+}]_f=1.0\times10^{-7}\,\text{M}\)) let \([\mathrm{HCO_3^-}]_f=x\).  
Using the equilibria:

\[
[\mathrm{H_2CO_3}]_f=\frac{[\mathrm{H}^{+}]_f x}{K_{a1}}=0.2222\,x,
\qquad
[\mathrm{CO_3^{2-}}]_f=\frac{K_{a2}x}{[\mathrm{H}^{+}]_f}=4.7\times10^{-4}\,x
\]

and the constancy of \(C_{\text{T}}\):

\[
x+0.2222x+4.7\times10^{-4}x=C_{\text{T}}
\;\Longrightarrow\;
x=\frac{C_{\text{T}}}{1.2227}=1.96\times10^{-2}\ \text{M}
\]

Thus

\[
[\mathrm{H_2CO_3}]_f=0.2222\,x=4.36\times10^{-3}\ \text{M}
\]

The increase in the amount of \(\mathrm{H_2CO_3}\) (and the tiny increase in free \(\mathrm{H}^{+}\)) equals the moles of added acid:

\[
\Delta n_{\text{acid}}=
\bigl([\mathrm{H_2CO_3}]_f-[\mathrm{H_2CO_3}]_i\bigr)
+([\mathrm{H}^{+}]_f-[\mathrm{H}^{+}]_i)
= (4.36-1.95)\times10^{-3}+6.0\times10^{-8}
\approx 2.41\times10^{-3}\ \text{mol}
\]

Hence, for a 1 dm³ (1 L) sample:

\[
\boxed{2.41\times10^{-3}}\ \text{mol}
\]

The salt \(\text{C}_6\text{H}_5\text{NH}_3\text{Cl}\) dissociates completely to give the weak‑acid cation \(\text{C}_6\text{H}_5\text{NH}_3^{+}\).  
Its acid dissociation constant is  

\[
K_a=\frac{K_w}{K_b(\text{aniline})}
      =\frac{1.0\times10^{-14}}{4.3\times10^{-10}}
      =2.33\times10^{-5}
\]

For the weak‑acid equilibrium  

\[
\text{C}_6\text{H}_5\text{NH}_3^{+}+ \text{H}_2\text{O}\rightleftharpoons 
\text{C}_6\text{H}_5\text{NH}_2 + \text{H}_3\text{O}^{+}
\]

let \(x=[\text{H}_3\text{O}^{+}]\).  The mass‑balance gives  

\[
K_a=\frac{x^{2}}{C_0-x},\qquad C_0=2.0\times10^{-4}\ \text{M}
\]

which leads to the quadratic  

\[
x^{2}+K_a x-K_a C_0=0
\]

\[
x=\frac{-K_a+\sqrt{K_a^{2}+4K_a C_0}}{2}
   =\frac{-2.33\times10^{-5}+\sqrt{(2.33\times10^{-5})^{2}+4(2.33\times10^{-5})(2.0\times10^{-4})}}{2}
   =5.8\times10^{-5}\ \text{M}
\]

Hence the hydronium‑ion concentration is  

\[
\boxed{5.8\times10^{-5}}\ \text{M}
\]

