The overall discharge reaction is  

\[
\mathrm{LiCoO_2}+6\,\mathrm{C}\;\longrightarrow\;\mathrm{CoO_2}+ \mathrm{LiC_6}
\]

Thus 1 mol of \(\mathrm{LiCoO_2}\) consumes 6 mol of graphite to give 1 mol of \(\mathrm{LiC_6}\).

---

**Moles initially present**

\[
\begin{aligned}
n_{\mathrm{LiCoO_2}} &=\frac{10.00\;\text{g}}{M_{\mathrm{LiCoO_2}}}
                     =\frac{10.00}{6.94+58.93+2(16.00)}
                     =\frac{10.00}{97.87}=0.1022\;\text{mol}\\[4pt]
n_{\mathrm{C}} &=\frac{10.00\;\text{g}}{12.01}=0.8326\;\text{mol}
\end{aligned}
\]

The required amount of graphite for the available \(\mathrm{LiCoO_2}\) is  

\[
6\,n_{\mathrm{LiCoO_2}} = 6(0.1022)=0.613\;\text{mol}
\]

Since \(0.8326\;\text{mol} > 0.613\;\text{mol}\), \(\mathrm{LiCoO_2}\) is the limiting reagent.

---

**Products formed**

\[
n_{\mathrm{LiC_6}} = n_{\mathrm{LiCoO_2}} = 0.1022\;\text{mol}
\]

Mass of \(\mathrm{LiC_6}\):

\[
M_{\mathrm{LiC_6}} = 6.94 + 6(12.01)=79.0\;\text{g mol}^{-1}
\]
\[
m_{\mathrm{LiC_6}} = 0.1022 \times 79.0 = 8.07\;\text{g}
\]

Remaining graphite:

\[
n_{\text{C,\,left}} = n_{\mathrm{C}}-6n_{\mathrm{LiCoO_2}}
                     =0.8326-0.613 =0.2196\;\text{mol}
\]
\[
m_{\text{C,\,left}} = 0.2196 \times 12.01 = 2.64\;\text{g}
\]

---

**Mass of the anode after complete discharge**

\[
m_{\text{anode}} = m_{\mathrm{LiC_6}} + m_{\text{C,\,left}}
                 = 8.07\;\text{g} + 2.64\;\text{g}
                 = 10.71\;\text{g}
\]

\[
\boxed{10.71}\ \text{g}
\]
